<?xml version="1.0"?><eml:eml xmlns:eml="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.1" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" packageId="huangym.9.6" system="knb" xsi:schemaLocation="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.1 eml.xsd" scope="system"><dataset scope="document"><title>Cryptic characteristics distinguish diploid and triploid varieties of Pteris fauriei (Pteridaceae)</title><creator id="1196056782812" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Yao-Moan</givenName><surName>Huang</surName></individualName><organizationName>TFRI</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>53, Nan-Hai Rd., Taipei, Taiwan</deliveryPoint><city>Taipei</city><administrativeArea>Taiwan</administrativeArea><postalCode>10066</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">886-23039978</phone><electronicMailAddress>huangym@tfri.gov.tw</electronicMailAddress></creator><creator id="1196056874468" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Hsueh-Mei</givenName><surName>Chou</surName></individualName><organizationName>Department of Life Science, National Taiwan Normal University</organizationName><address scope="document"><city>Taipei</city><administrativeArea>Taiwan</administrativeArea><postalCode>100</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address></creator><creator id="1196056985187" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Tsung-Hsin</givenName><surName>Hsieh</surName></individualName><organizationName>Department of Natural Science Education, National University of Tainan</organizationName><address scope="document"><city>Tainan</city><administrativeArea>Taiwan</administrativeArea><country>Taiwan</country></address></creator><creator id="1196057061156" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Wen-Liang</givenName><surName>Chiou</surName></individualName><organizationName>TFRI</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>53, Nan-Hai Rd., Taipei, Taiwan</deliveryPoint><city>Taipei</city><administrativeArea>Taiwan</administrativeArea><postalCode>10066</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">886-2-23039978</phone><electronicMailAddress>chiou@tfri.gov.tw</electronicMailAddress></creator><abstract><para>Sporophytes of Pteris fauriei var. fauriei and P. fauriei var. minor were difficult to distinguish based only on the morphology of mature fronds. However, we found the two varieties can be distinguished based on spore size, the number of spores in each sporangium, the number of sperm in each antheridium, antheridium size, reproductive behavior, and the morphology of juvenile sporophyte embryos and fronds. Using spore size, the specimens of P. fauriei var. fauriei and P. fauriei var. minor collected by Père Urbain Faurie in 1904, and published by Hieronymus (1914), are triploid and diploid, respectively.</para></abstract><keywordSet><keyword>apomixis</keyword><keyword>gametophyte</keyword><keyword>juvenile sporophyte</keyword><keyword>Pteridaceae</keyword><keyword>Pteris fauriei</keyword><keyword>reproductive biology</keyword></keywordSet><intellectualRights><para>Cryptic characteristics distinguish diploid and triploid varieties of Pteris fauriei (Pteridaceae)</para></intellectualRights><coverage scope="document"><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>Taiwan</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>119.125</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>122.5</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>26.0</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>21.875</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates></geographicCoverage><temporalCoverage scope="document"><rangeOfDates><beginDate><calendarDate>2001-01-01</calendarDate></beginDate><endDate><calendarDate>2005-12-31</calendarDate></endDate></rangeOfDates></temporalCoverage><taxonomicCoverage scope="document"><taxonomicClassification><taxonRankName>Genus</taxonRankName><taxonRankValue>Pteris</taxonRankValue><taxonomicClassification><taxonRankName>Species</taxonRankName><taxonRankValue>fauriei</taxonRankValue></taxonomicClassification></taxonomicClassification></taxonomicCoverage></coverage><contact id="1196057155703" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Wen-Liang</givenName><surName>Chiou</surName></individualName><organizationName>TFRI</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>53, Nan-Hai Rd., Taipei, Taiwan</deliveryPoint><city>Taipei</city><administrativeArea>Taiwan</administrativeArea><postalCode>10066</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">886-2-23039978</phone><electronicMailAddress>chiou@tfri.gov.tw</electronicMailAddress></contact><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Cryptic characteristics distinguish diploid and triploid varieties of Pteris fauriei (Pteridaceae)</title><para>Eighteen plants were collected from 3 populations in Taiwan, 6 plants in each population: along the seashore at Yehliu, Taipei county (25° 12&apos; 30&quot; N, 121° 40&apos; 08&quot; E, elevation 2-10 m), the forest at Fushan, Ilan county (24° 16&apos; 50&quot; N, 121° 34&apos; 48&quot; E, elevation 760-780 m), and along the seashore at Chialoshue, Pingtung county (21° 58&apos; 10&quot; N, 120° 47&apos; 26&quot; E, elevation 5-10 m). They were transplanted to the fern greenhouse of the Taiwan Forestry Research Institute (TFRI). After 1 month in cultivation, the root tips of sporophytes were pretreated for 3-4 h with a mixture of 70 ppm cycloheximide and 250 ppm 8-hydroxyquinoline (1:1) at about 18-20℃. The root tips were fixed for 1-3 h in a mixture of 45% acetic acid and absolute ethanol (1:3) at about 20℃, and then preserved in 70% ethanol at 4℃. Then they were macerated for 1-3 min in 1 N HCl at 60℃, washed for 10 sec and digested for 1-2 h in 4 % pectinase. Finally, the root tips were squashed in modified Sharma’s solution (Sharma 1982). The number of chromosomes in root-tip cells was observed with light microscopes (Leica, Wild M8; Leitz, Dialux 20) and photographed with a digital camera (Nikon, Coolpix 995).</para><para>Mature fronds were collected and the number of spores was counted in each of 10 randomly selected sporangia from each plant. Then the fronds were air-dried for two days to release the spores. The diameter of 100 randomly selected spores from each plant was measured within two days of release. Diploid and triploid plants were identified by chromosome count and the spores of each were sown separately on Kingroot medium (vermiculite: peat: perlite = 4:4:2; South Sea Vermiculite and Perlite Co., Taipei, Taiwan). Cultures were maintained under white fluorescent illumination at about 24 μmole m-2s-1, 12 h/d. Temperature ranged from 20 to 28℃.</para><para>The sexual expression, age and size of 100 randomly selected gametophytes from each plant were recorded every two weeks. Gametophytes bearing antheridia, five from diploid plants and five from triploid plants, were immersed in FAA solution (formaldehyde: acetic acid: 50% ethanol = 5: 5: 90) for a week. Five antheridia from each gametophyte were sampled, and the number of sperm in each antheridium was counted. Reproductive behavior and the appearance of young sporophytes, both sexual and apomictic, were monitored.</para><para>The morphology of gametophytes and young sporophytes was observed with light microscopes (Leica, Wild M8; Leitz, Dialux 20) and photographed with a digital camera (Nikon, Coolpix 995). To observe the fine morphology of spores, air-dried spores were mounted on double-stick mending tape, coated with gold, and imaged with a Hitachi S2400 Scanning Electron Microscope.</para><para>A syntype of Pteris fauriei var. fauriei (Faurie 628) and an isotype of P. fauriei var. minor (Faurie 685) were on loan from the Natural History Museum (BM), London, UK. The equatorial diameter of 100 spores from each specimen was measured. The fine structure of each specimen was observed as described above.</para></section></description></methodStep><sampling><studyExten